04664nam a22006135i 9781571137197DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20102010xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97815711371977 a10.1515/97815711371972doi  a(DE-B1597)675009  a(OCoLC)1420507502  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aMUS0200002bisacsh04a780.921 aNiekerk, Carl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReading Mahler :bGerman Culture and Jewish Identity in Fin-de-Siècle Vienna /cCarl Niekerk.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2010] 1bCamden House, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (322 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in German Literature Linguistics and Culture ;v8700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction: Literature, Philosophy, and Images in Mahler’s Music -- tI. The Crisis of German Culture -- t1: Titan: Symphony of an Anti-Hero -- t2: Des Knaben Wunderhorn: Rediscovering the “Volk” -- t3: Nietzsche and the Crisis of German Culture -- tII. German Culture and Its Others -- t4: Rembrandt and the Margins of German Culture -- t5: Goethe against German Culture -- t6: The Two Faces of German Orientalism -- tConclusion: Beyond Mahler -- tNotes -- tWorks Consulted -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExamines literary, philosophical, and cultural influences on Mahler's thought and work from the standpoint of the composer's position in German-Jewish culture.Gustav Mahler's music is more popular than ever, yet few are aware of its roots in German literary and cultural history in general, and in fin-de-siècle Viennese culture in particular. Taking as its point of departure the many references to literature, philosophy, and the visual arts that Mahler uses to illustrate the meaning of his music, Reading Mahler helps audiences, critics, and those interested in musical and cultural history understand influences on Mahler's music and thinking that may have been self-evident to middle-class Viennese a hundred years ago but are much more obscure today. It shows that Mahler's oeuvre, despite its reliance on texts and images from the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries, is far more indebted to fin-de-siècle modernism and to an eclectic, proto-avantgardist agenda than has been previously realized. Furthermore, Reading Mahler is the first book to make Mahler's position within German-Jewish culture its analytical center. It also probes Mahler's problematic but often overlooked relationship with the musical and textual legacy of Richard Wagner. By integrating newer approaches in humanistic research - cultural studies, gender studies, and Jewish studies - Reading Mahler exposes the composer's critical view of German cultural history and offers a new understanding of his music. Carl Niekerk is Professor in the Department of German, the Program in Comparative and World Literature, and the Program in Jewish Culture and Society at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGerman literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aMusic and literature. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aFin-de-Siècle.  aGerman-Jewish Culture.  aGustav Mahler.  aMusical and Cultural History.  aViennese Culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781571137197?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781571137197423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781571137197/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Co